# openclaw-biohub

**Your wearables, labs, and supplements — one place, on your hardware.**

A self-hosted personal-health hub for [OpenClaw](https://docs.openclaw.ai/)
and adjacent quantified-self setups. Pulls biometric data from wearables,
parses your blood-panel PDFs, tracks your supplement stack, ships a
Next.js dashboard, and gives your agent a `SKILL.md` for grounded
wellness coaching. WHOOP is the first adapter wired end-to-end; Fitbit,
Garmin, Oura and Apple Health are designed to slot in as siblings.

Tracks **recovery score, HRV (rmssd), resting heart rate, SpO₂, skin
temperature, sleep stages (REM / deep / light), sleep efficiency, daily
strain, workouts with HR zones, body composition, glucose / CGM,
blood-panel biomarkers** (with reference-range flagging), and
**supplement intake with lag-aware partial-correlation analysis** against
recovery and HRV. Includes an ML pattern engine (Pearson correlations,
IsolationForest anomaly detection, linear-regression recommendations).

> ⚠️ **Not medical advice.** See [DISCLAIMER.md](DISCLAIMER.md).

## What's in the box

| Piece | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| **`pipeline/adapters/`** | One subdir per device source (`whoop/` today, `fitbit/`, `garmin/`, … next). Each adapter writes into the normalized DB. |
| **`pipeline/`** | Source-agnostic helpers: blood-panel PDF parser, biomarker + supplement analytics, ML pattern engine, shared path resolution. |
| **`dashboard/`** | Next.js 16 / React 19 dashboard with recovery, sleep, strain, blood-work, and supplement tabs. |
| **`agent/`** | OpenClaw "wellness coach" persona files (SOUL.md, AGENTS.md, USER.md template). Drop-in for an OpenClaw agent definition. |
| **`systemd/`** | A `whoop-oauth-handler.service` unit + `secrets.env.example` for production deploys. |
| **`db/schema.sql`** | Schema for the two SQLite databases: `health.db` (normalized — blood / supplements / nutrition / daily rollup from any source) and `whoop_raw.db` (raw WHOOP API payloads; future adapters get their own `*_raw.db`). |
| **`fixtures/`** | `seed.py` produces 90 days of deterministic synthetic data so you can poke at the system before pointing it at real credentials. |

## Multi-device design

The repo is organized so that adding a new wearable means dropping a new
folder into `pipeline/adapters/` and a new `*_raw.db` table block into
`db/schema.sql`. The dashboard, the agent persona, and the analytics tier
all read from the normalized `health.db` — they don't know or care which
source the data came from. WHOOP is the first one wired up end-to-end;
contributions for Fitbit / Garmin / Oura / Apple Health are welcome (see
[CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md)).

## Five-minute quickstart

Prerequisites: Python 3.11+, Node 20+, `sqlite3`.

```bash
# 1. Clone + pick a workspace
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USER/openclaw-biohub
cd openclaw-biohub
export OPENCLAW_BIOHUB_HOME=$PWD/.local-data

# 2. Install Python deps
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r pipeline/requirements.txt

# 3. Seed synthetic data so the dashboard has something to render
python3 fixtures/seed.py

# 4. Start the dashboard
cd dashboard
npm install
npm run dev
# → open http://localhost:3000 (auto-redirects to /health)
```

To hook up real WHOOP data instead of fixtures, see
[CONFIGURATION.md](CONFIGURATION.md).

## What the dashboard shows

- **Recovery** — recovery score, HRV (rmssd), resting HR, SpO₂, skin temp.
- **Strain** — daily strain, workout strain, calories, HR zones.
- **Sleep** — duration, performance %, efficiency %, REM / deep / light breakdown, consistency.
- **Trends** — 7-day, 30-day, 90-day baselines and deltas.
- **Blood work** — biomarker time series, reference-range flagging.
- **Supplements** — intake log + Pearson correlation against recovery / HRV
  (lag-aware, controlling for sleep and strain).

The optional `health-insights` endpoint runs `whoop_pattern_engine.py`
which does pairwise Pearson correlations, IsolationForest anomaly
detection, and linear-regression-based recommendations.

## Project layout

```
openclaw-biohub/
├── pipeline/
│   ├── adapters/
│   │   └── whoop/                   # WHOOP API → whoop_raw.db
│   │       ├── sync.py
│   │       ├── oauth_handler.py
│   │       ├── webhook_handler.py
│   │       ├── backfill_sleep.py
│   │       └── backfill_zones.py
│   ├── whoop_pattern_engine.py      # ML analytics over whoop_raw.db
│   ├── parse_blood_panel.py         # lab PDF parser
│   ├── blood_marker_analytics.py
│   ├── supplement_analytics.py
│   ├── fix_blood_markers.py
│   ├── paths.py                     # env-driven path resolution
│   └── requirements.txt
├── dashboard/                       # Next.js dashboard
├── agent/                           # OpenClaw wellness-coach persona
├── systemd/                         # WHOOP OAuth handler service
├── db/schema.sql                    # health.db + whoop_raw.db
├── fixtures/                        # seed.py + sample blood panel
├── tests/                           # pytest suite
└── .github/workflows/ci.yml
```

## Adding a new device adapter

For someone wiring up Fitbit, Garmin, Oura, or another source:

1. Add a new `db/schema.sql` block for the raw DB (`fitbit_raw.db`, etc.) —
   one table per resource the API exposes.
2. Create `pipeline/adapters/<source>/` with `sync.py` (+ `oauth_handler.py`
   if the source uses OAuth + a refresh-token flow). Mirror the WHOOP
   adapter's pattern.
3. Extend `daily_metrics` (or rename it to `daily`) in `health.db` with the
   fields your adapter emits — the dashboard reads from `health.db`, not
   the raw DBs.
4. Add fixtures to `fixtures/seed.py` and tests under `tests/`.

The whole point of the adapter pattern is that none of the dashboard /
agent / analytics code should need to change.

## How it fits with OpenClaw

If you run [OpenClaw](https://github.com/openclaw) (or another agent
harness):

1. Drop `agent/` into your agent definitions directory.
2. Customize `agent/USER.md` (your name, baselines, notification preferences).
3. Point `OPENCLAW_BIOHUB_HOME` at where the DBs and credentials live.
4. The agent reads from `health.db` / `whoop_raw.db` via the queries
   documented in `agent/AGENTS.md`.

The dashboard and agent are independent — you can use either alone.

## Status

`v0.x` — the API and DB schema may change between minor versions while
the project finds its feet. Tag-based releases will note any breakage.

